review:
I'll analyze this PR for correctness bugs, focusing on null safety, logic errors, and error handling.

---

## Code Review: useUser Hook

[SEVERITY: HIGH] Line 22, 26, 29 — Missing `setLoading(false)` after fetch completes  
Category: logic  
Detail: The `setLoading(false)` call is missing after the try/catch block. This means `isLoading` will remain `true` indefinitely after the first fetch starts, even when data is loaded or an error occurs. Add `setLoading(false)` in both the try and catch branches (or use a finally block).

[SEVERITY: HIGH] Line 21–31 — Stale request race condition when userId changes  
Category: logic  
Detail: When `userId` changes while a fetch is in flight, the old fetch's promise will still resolve and call `setUser()`, overwriting the new user data. This causes brief display of wrong data. Use `AbortController` to cancel in-flight requests when the effect re-runs or the component unmounts.

[SEVERITY: HIGH] Line 21–31 — Missing cleanup causes memory leak on unmount  
Category: null_safety / memory  
Detail: The effect has no cleanup function. If the component unmounts while a fetch is in flight, the promise will still try to call `setState` on an unmounted component, triggering React warnings and leaks. Return a cleanup function that cancels the fetch using `AbortController` or sets a `mounted` flag.

[SEVERITY: MEDIUM] Line 25 — Stale error state after successful fetch  
Category: logic  
Detail: On successful fetch, `setUser(data)` is called but `setError(null)` is not. If a previous fetch failed, the old error message will remain visible alongside the new user data. Add `setError(null)` in the try block before setting the user.

[SEVERITY: MEDIUM] Line 16 — Type safety: `any` defeats TypeScript  
Category: type_safety  
Detail: `useState<any>(null)` should be `useState<User | null>(null)` to ensure the returned `user` value is properly typed and callers know what shape to expect.

---

**Recommended fix** — use `AbortController` + `setLoading(false)` in a finally block:

```typescript
useEffect(() => {
  const controller = new AbortController();

  const load = async () => {
    setLoading(true);
    setError(null);  // Clear old error
    try {
      const data = await fetchUser(userId);
      setUser(data);
    } catch (err) {
      if (!controller.signal.aborted) {
        setError(err instanceof Error ? err : new Error('Fetch failed'));
      }
    } finally {
      setLoading(false);  // Always clear loading state
    }
  };

  load();
  return () => controller.abort();  // Cleanup
}, [userId]);
```
